"1214–1302","1253–1321":"1253–1321","1234–1299":"1234–1299","1170–1221":"1170–1221","1170–Female":"1170–Overleden","Bef 28 June 1221":"vóór 28 juni 1221","1253":"1253","Bef 26 December 1258":"vóór 26 december 1258","1170":"1170","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1302":"1302","1214":"1214","1258":"1258","1224":"1224","Abt 1200":"circa 1200","1234":"1234","1299":"1299","1321":"1321","1200":"1200","1221":"1221","Hartland, Devonshire, England":"Hartland, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Buckland Dinham, Somerset, England":"Buckland Dinham, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Harpford, Honiton, Devon, England":"Harpford, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hartland, Devon, England":"Hartland, Devon, England"},"en":{"Abt 1200–Bef 26 December 1258":"about 1200–before 26 December 1258","1200–1238":"1200–1238","1200–1258":"1200–1258","1214–1302":"1214–1302","1253–1321":"1253–1321","1234–1299":"1234–1299","1170–1221":"1170–1221","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","Bef 28 June 1221":"before 28 June 1221","1253":"1253","Bef 26 December 1258":"before 26 December 1258","1170":"1170","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1302":"1302","1214":"1214","1258":"1258","1224":"1224","Abt 1200":"about 1200","1234":"1234","1299":"1299","1321":"1321","1200":"1200","1221":"1221","Hartland, Devonshire, England":"Hartland, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Buckland Dinham, Somerset, England":"Buckland Dinham, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Harpford, Honiton, Devon, England":"Harpford, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Hartland, Devon, England":"Hartland, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dinham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Dinham (Monmouths)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Geoffrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic (Frankish and Lombard) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It was in regular use among the counts of Anjou, ancestors of the English royal house of Plantagenet, who were descended from Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou (  1113–51 ). It was a particularly popular name in England and France in the later Middle Ages; notable bearers in England include the poet  Geoffrey Chaucer  (  <i>c.</i>1340–1400 ) and in Wales the chronicler  Geoffrey  of Monmouth (  d. 1155 ). The original form and meaning of the name is disputed. According to one theory, it is merely a variant of   Godfrey ;  others derive the first part from the Germanic word <i>gawia</i> ‘territory’, <i>walah</i> ‘stranger’, or <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. Medieval forms can be found to support all these theories, and it is possible that several names have fallen together, or that the name was subjected to reanalysis by folk etymology at an early date."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":24,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Geoffrey Dinham was born about 1200, in Hartland, Devon, England, his father, Oliver de Dinham, was 32 and his mother, Elizabeth, was 31. He had at least 1 son with Sarah Hornacote. His occupation is listed as lord de dinan in Dinan, Côtes-du-Nord, Brittan